  "The matrix G with entries G_ij = <v_i, v_j>": "",
  "The inverse of the matrix [v1 | ... | vk]": "",
  "The matrix whose columns are v1, ..., vk": "",
  "The Gram matrix G has entries G_ij = <v_i, v_j>. It is always positive semi-definite, and it is positive definite if and only if the vectors are linearly independent.": "",
  "A signal processing engineer defines an inner product on the space of square-integrable functions on [0, 2pi] as <f, g> = integral of f(x)g(x)dx. She computes <sin(x), cos(x)> over [0, 2pi]. What is the result?": "",
  "2pi": "",
  "pi": "",
  "Integral from 0 to 2pi of sin(x)cos(x)dx = (1/2) integral of sin(2x)dx = [-cos(2x)/4] from 0 to 2pi = (-1/4) - (-1/4) = 0. Sin and cos are orthogonal under this inner product.": "",
  "A statistician models data using a weighted inner product <u, v> = 3u1*v1 + u2*v2 on R^2. She wants to find the norm of the vector (2, 4). What is ||( 2, 4)||?": "",
  "sqrt(12)": "",
  "sqrt(28)": "",
  "sqrt(20)": "",
  "sqrt(52)": "",
  "||v||^2 = <v,v> = 3(2)(2) + 1(4)(4) = 12 + 16 = 28. So ||v|| = sqrt(28) = 2sqrt(7).": "",
  "A physicist working with Fourier analysis needs to show that sin(nx) and sin(mx) are orthogonal on [0, pi] when n != m (n, m positive integers). Which inner product does she use?": "",
  "<f, g> = f(pi/2) * g(pi/2)": "",
